Democracy Summit Ends, Biden Says Fire of Freedom Never Goes Out
The virtual Summit for Democracy, convened by President Biden of the United States and attended by leaders of governments and civil society and the private sector from 110 countries around the world, concluded Friday (December 10).
In his closing speech, Biden said that the fire of freedom burned in the hearts of everyone in the world and could never be extinguished by an authoritarian regime.
He also said he plans to hold a second global "democracy summit" next year.
Tang Feng, a Taiwanese government representative and councillor, and Luo Guancong, a Hong Kong democratic human rights activist currently in exile in the United Kingdom, also spoke at the next day's summit.
Biden said, "We know how difficult the work ahead of us is.
But we also know that we can meet the challenge, because I said before that, as this summit shows, the democratic world is everywhere.
Authoritarian regimes can never extinguish the tiny fire of freedom, which burns in the hearts of people all over the world and around the world."
Biden also said defending democracy required a joint effort by society as a whole.
"As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, to reinforce the barriers of democracy, to push for reform, to achieve transparent and accountable governance, to be more resilient to authoritarian cushions and shocks, and to those who want to pursue power nakedly before the public good," he said."
The next day of the "Democracy Summit" was devoted to defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authority, and countering digital authority and affirming democratic values.
The day coincides with International Human Rights Day.
In his opening speech that day, UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres also said that the cause of democracy faces global challenges, especially those posed by emerging digital technologies.
"It is time to reaffirm shared values and positions and democratic resilience," he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequalities, combating corruption, renewing social contracts, investing in quality education and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires a firm condemnation of all forms of populism, indigenousism, and extremism, including the use of all the tools offered by the technological revolution."
Luo Guancong, a democratic human rights activist in Hong Kong, addressed the summit via pre-recorded video, reminding participants to keep an eye on the human rights situation of ethnic minorities in China, such as Hong Kong and Uighurs and Tibetans.
"The world has long embraced China's rise without establishing a mechanism to hold it accountable," he said.
That is why politicians and civil society leaders must cooperate.
We must use everything we have to ensure that the revival of democracy is our top priority."
Luo Guancong also called on the free world to unite against the threat of the CPC.
"Maybe some of you are afraid to annoy General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the China market, maybe some of you don't recognize the threat to our democratic values.
And that's why we failed.
That's why we have to change."
In attending a round-table discussion on "Combating Digital Authoritarianism and Affirming Democratic Values," Taiwan's executive councillor, Tang Feng, released a National Statement via video, emphasizing that Taiwan is at the forefront of confronting authoritarianism and authority.
He also shared his experience on how to fight COVID-19 through information transparency and building mutual trust.
"We have always been firmly at the forefront of the global confrontation against authoritarianism and have taken a leadership role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights," he said.
During the pandemic, authoritarian governments around the world rationalized human rights violations in the name of public health and collective interests, and global democracy showed signs of regression.
However, in Taiwan, we can control the epidemic without lockdown, and we can defeat false information without removing it."
In parallel with the agenda of the second day of the Democratic Summit, the United States Department of the Treasury announced sanctions against 15 individuals and 10 entities in several countries, including China and North Korea, who were found to have committed serious human rights violations, and imposed investment restrictions on a Chinese company that was found to have used surveillance technology to assist in human rights violations.
