Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected GCC internal solidarity and have had a negative impact on the economies of the countries of the region.
Four Arab countries have blocked land, sea and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was resolved only at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, when the Gulf states signed an agreement between the United States and Kuwait to mediate towards "solidarity and stability".
Saudi Arabia reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are leading efforts to restore relations with Qatar through the appointment of new ambassadors in Qatar.
Resolving differences to restore relations with Qatar in the Arab States of the Gulf stems from the need to unite in the interests of States and regional stability, aimed at addressing common challenges.
