A 725-kilometer corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate travel and supply chain integration for citizens of both countries.
The Saudi Arabia Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest USD 5 billion in Oman, and 13 memorandums of understanding worth USD 30 billion have been signed between the two countries.
Saudi Arabia's visit to the Gulf states coincided with talks between Iran and the world's major powers over the salvage of the Iran nuclear deal, known as the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA), an agreement condemned by the Gulf's Arab states for perceived inability to resolve their missile problems with Iran.
The Gulf states have long regarded Iran as a long-term "rival" and Iran's nuclear program as a "threat" to regional security.
The Gulf States consider it flawed to fail to address Iran's missile problem and to act to curb Iran's activities in the region.
Saudi Arabia held direct talks with Iran in the context of the failure of major powers to meet the aspirations of the Gulf states in their nuclear talks with Iran.
The goal is to contain the escalation of tension in the region.
This is one of the factors which slows economic growth in GCC countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first of its kind since the end of a dispute between some member states and Qatar.
This is an opportunity for the GCC to reassess the diplomatic outcomes that contribute to the restoration of GCC unity, while proposing measures to allow its member States to cooperate fully to address common challenges and contribute to the stability and development of the Gulf States.
